Release Detection



?       Hydrocarbon detectors with alarms in the liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) storage and other areas;

?       Hydrofluoric acid detectors with alarms in the HF Alkylation Unit;

?       H2S detectors in compressor buildings where H2S may be present;

?       Light oil storage tanks include automatic level gauges and high level alarms. 



Release Containment/Control



?       Process relief valves that discharge to a flare to capture and combust process materials to prevent overpressure damage to equipment;

?       Scrubber to neutralize hydrofluoric acid releases to the flare in the HF Alkylation Unit;

?       Prevention, Detection and Mitigation (PDM) System in the HF Alkylation Unit;

?       Manual and automatic valves (Emergency Isolation Valves) to permit isolation of equipment or process units;

?       Automated Emergency Shutdown Systems (ESDs) for specific process parameters (e.g., high level, high temperature);

?       Curbing or diking to contain liquid releases;    

?       Redundant equipment and instrumentation where needed (e.g., uninterruptible power supply for process control system, redundant firewater pumps);

?       Water spray systems;

?       Fire suppression and extinguishing systems;

?       Emergency Response Team (ERT) equipment (fire trucks/response equipment e.g., spill cleanup equip, booms);

?       Light oil storage tanks include release prevention barriers under the floors and lined containment dikes.



Other



?       Trained emergency response personnel;

?       Personal protective equipment (e.g., protective clothing, personal H2S monitors, self-contained breathing apparatus);

?       Structurally adequate control buildings to help protect control systems and personnel in the event of an explosion;

?       Emergency Warning Horn (evacuation or shelter-in-place).



1.6  Five-year Accident History



