meetings which include local emergency response officials, local government officials, and industry representatives. SPPRC has around-the-clock communications capability with appropriate government officials and emergency response organizations (e.g., fire department).  This provides a means of notifying the public of an incident, if necessary, as well as facilitating quick response to an incident.  In addition to participating in periodic mutual aid meetings, SPPRC conducts periodic emergency drills that involve emergency response organizations, and the refinery provides periodic refresher training to local emergency responders regarding the hazards of regulated substances in the refinery. 



1.8      Planned Changes to Improve Safety



SPPRC constantly strives to improve the safety of its operations through periodic safety reviews, the incident investigation program, and a program soliciting safety suggestions from the workers.  SPPRC resolves all findings from PHAs, some of which result in modifications to the process.  



The following types of changes are planned during the next 5 years:



?      Alky Quantitative Risk Analysis (QRA) Upgrades - Supplemental HF release mitigation upgrades consisting of an additional water mitigation curtain around acid circulating equipment and an automated shutdown/isolation system based on signals from local HF detectors;

?      Relief System Improvements - Redesign and replacement of the HDH flare knockout drum to comply with the requirements of API 520 and 521 by increasing the  of the knockout drum;

?      Tank Rundown Temperature Indication - Installation of temperature monitoring equipment and alarm instrumentation for rundown streams to storage tanks that have the potential for hazardous releases due to the presence of water or product vaporization;

?      Elimination of Threaded Pipe - Implement a project to identify threaded piping components in hydrocarbon service in need of replacement to eliminate the potential for leakage

as a result of thermal expansion;

?      Replacing the fire water distribution header, and;

?      Eliminating ring joint flange gaskets in reformer units.
